Disc herniation is one of the most frequently diagnosed spinal conditions — and one of the most misunderstood. Many patients arrive at our clinic convinced they need surgery, only to discover that conservative chiropractic care can provide significant relief without the risks, costs, and recovery time associated with surgical intervention.

## What Is a Disc Herniation?

The intervertebral discs are fibrocartilaginous cushions that sit between each pair of vertebrae. Each disc consists of two parts:

- **Annulus fibrosus** — The tough, layered outer ring made of concentric collagen fibres
- **Nucleus pulposus** — The gel-like centre that acts as a hydraulic shock absorber

A herniation occurs when the nucleus pulposus pushes through a tear or weakness in the annulus fibrosus. Depending on the direction and severity of the herniation, the displaced material may press on nearby spinal nerves or the spinal cord itself.

The progression typically follows these stages:

1. Disc degeneration — The disc loses hydration and becomes less resilient
1. Disc bulge — The nucleus shifts but remains contained within the annulus
1. Disc protrusion — The nucleus pushes into but does not break through the outer layers
1. Disc extrusion — The nucleus breaks through the annulus but remains attached
1. Disc sequestration — A fragment of nucleus separates completely (the most severe stage)

## What Causes Disc Herniation?

Disc injuries are rarely caused by a single event. In most cases, they result from cumulative microtrauma — repeated stress that gradually weakens the annular fibres until they fail. Contributing factors include:

- **Prolonged sitting** — Sitting increases intradiscal pressure by up to 40% compared to standing, particularly when the lower back is unsupported
- **Poor lifting mechanics** — Bending and twisting under load places asymmetric shear forces on the disc
- **Repetitive flexion** — Occupations or sports that involve repeated forward bending accelerate annular wear
- **Dehydration and age** — Discs lose water content over time, reducing their ability to absorb shock
- **Genetic predisposition** — Some individuals have thinner or weaker annular fibres

